              <DefinitionShort>pertaining to being the color of the flower hyacinth (see {D:2.41}), probably a shade of blue</DefinitionShort>
              <Glosses>
                <Gloss>blue</Gloss>
              </Glosses>
              <Comments>Since in some languages the flower hyacinth may not be as well known as precious stones such as sapphire and turquoise, it may be possible to render {S:06600901700036} as ‘blue as sapphire’ or ‘blue as turquoise.’ The justification for this is simply that the Greek term ὑακίνθινος had become primarily a designation for color.</Comments>
